{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523422"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13896"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13896"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.35,0.15,0.21,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100417"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6515"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13896"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82821"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4561"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12999"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34487"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48284"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100417"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with worsening abdominal discomfort and constipation. She has a long history of gut motility problems and requires numerous medications for her chronic constipation. She has no significant medical history other than her gastrointestinal issues and takes no regular medications except for her constipation treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Her abdomen is distended but soft, with diffuse tenderness on palpation. There are no signs of peritonism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbdominal X-rays are performed as below (image). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis based on the radiological findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Small bowel obstruction","Diaphragmatic hernia","Sigmoid volvulus","Pneumoperitoneum","Chilaiditi syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the radiological findings described, particularly the presence of a loop of bowel above the right lobe of the liver, the most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003EChilaiditi syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This rare condition is characterised by the interposition of the colon (usually the transverse colon) between the liver and the diaphragm. It is often an incidental finding on imaging but can be associated with symptoms in some cases, particularly in patients with chronic constipation or gut motility disorders, as in this case. It may be painful and associated with a distended abdomen, change in bowel habits or dyspnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a dilated sigmoid colon on X-ray, often described as a \u0027coffee bean\u0027 appearance. While this patient has dilated loops of large bowel, the specific finding of bowel above the liver is not characteristic of sigmoid volvulus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E would typically show dilated loops of small bowel with air-fluid levels on an abdominal X-ray. The description of dilated large bowel and the loop above the liver is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumoperitoneum\u003C/strong\u003E, or free air in the peritoneal cavity, would appear as a crescent of air under the diaphragm on an upright chest X-ray. The description of a loop of bowel above the liver is not consistent with pneumoperitoneum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiaphragmatic hernia\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause bowel to appear above the liver, but it would typically be associated with a defect in the diaphragm, which is not mentioned in the radiological findings. Chilaiditi syndrome, in contrast, occurs without a diaphragmatic defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement typically involves conservative measures such as bowel decompression, hydration, and addressing the underlying constipation. This may be from chronic constipation, ascites, multiparity or congenital malposition. Surgical intervention is rarely necessary unless there are complications or persistent symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic constipation and gut motility disorders can lead to colonic distension and potential complications like Chilaiditi syndrome."],"references":["Jones J, Bell D, Elfeky M, et al. Chilaiditi syndrome. Radiopaedia. 2024. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/chilaiditi-syndrome","Guerra F, Sacchetti R. Chilaiditi syndrome. An uncommon cause of crampy, upper abdominal pain.  Annals of Hepatology. 2016: 15 (5).  Available at: https://www.elsevier.es/en-revista-annals-hepatology-16-articulo-chilaiditi-syndrome-an-uncommon-cause-S1665268119306416"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82821"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13896"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20835"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20835"}